initiate contraction","ATP is not required for the detachment of myosin from actin","Myosin heads bind permanently to actin during contraction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of cross bridges between actin and myosin\u003C/strong\u003E generates a power stroke that pulls actin filaments towards the sarcomere centre, causing muscle contraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle shortening occurs by movement of thick filaments over thin filaments\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as thin filaments slide over thick filaments to produce muscle shortening, not vice versa. \u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium ions bind to myosin heads\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because calcium binds to troponin, not myosin heads, acting to expose actin binding sites. \u003Cstrong\u003EATP is not required for the detachment of myosin from actin\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since ATP hydrolysis is essential for myosin detachment from actin. \u003Cstrong\u003EMyosin heads bind permanently to actin during contraction\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as myosin heads repeatedly attach and detach from actin during the cross-bridge cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sliding filament model explains muscle contraction through the interaction of actin and myosin filaments.","Cross-bridge formation between actin and myosin is essential for the power stroke, leading to muscle contraction.","Muscle shortening occurs as thin filaments slide over thick filaments."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 6; pg. 82","Patton KT, Thibodeau GA. Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2018.","Hutson M, Ward A, editors. Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press; 2015.","